It contains Tender Beef, served on Rice with Smoked Bacon Barbecue Sauce, Boiled Egg, and Green Onions. I didn't really get a loco moco vibe from the dish. The beef was tender (albeit a bit dry) but was overpowered by the barbecue sauce. It was hard to taste the other components like the egg and onions. insta_description:
Good morning friends.  We made it to our destination safely.  Haha. As I was walking this morning on the lake, I thought of how much God loves us and cares about us.  America has been blessed down through history because our founding fathers put God first and tried to make us one nation under God. Yet we have taken prayer out of schools and pushed God away. We now have a generation who knows not the power of prayer. The God that holds our very breath and who wondrously created us has been shunned.  Then we wonder why America is having all the trials that we are having. Where had America gone? Where have the prayer warriors gone? America needs to wake up and fall on her knees and pray that God in His judgment will remember mercy and bring us back to where we started from. God loved America and cares so much about our every need.  Isnt it time to thank Him and praise Him for blessing us like He has? We could be a nation gone under but yet we're still blessed.  A God who truly loves us just wants  you and I to love Him and praise Him
 Isnt it time to get back to the basics before it's too late? He loves us and wants to bless us. We can find peace in the midst of our storms.

insta_description:
Working from home? Finding the days just draaaaaaag on? I‚Äôve been doing online work for the past 4 years, so I‚Äôve learned exactly how to stay productive and efficient, whether in a coworking space or at home. Here are some of my top tips (save this post!).
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Get outta your PJs üõè While it can be sooooo tempting to stay in comfy sweatpants all day, putting on normal clothes and getting ready for the day as if I was working out of the house really increases my productivity.

Write a master to-do list ‚úÖ Break down every little thing you need to do into steps and add it to the checklist! Being able to see your progress throughout the day helps keep the momentum going.

Take meals away from work üçù LEAVE THE LAPTOP. When you work from home, it‚Äôs so important to separate you-time from work-time. Eat your meals away from your makeshift desk, and work your normal hours.

Use your calendar! üìÖ I am a slave to my google calendar. I love to schedule out every single minute of my day into blocks. Blocks for each task, blocks for scheduled break times, blocks for free time at the end of the day. It helps me stay on track between tasks and to get everything I need done.

Get some sunshine üåû Working environment is everything when you‚Äôre at home. I like to have a proper desk and pleeenty of natural light. Find what works for you and keep it a space for productivity!

Say NO to multitasking. üì∫ You probably won‚Äôt do your best work while watching Love is Blind.

The takeaway - get super organised and keep your work and home life separate! Boundaries & organisation are key üîë

Are all of you working from home? Have any other tips to share?

A lot of great writers have come out of LA, and on this virtual tour: I give you John Fante‚Äôs, Ask the Dust, set in Los Angeles during the Great Depression, an intoxicating time in LA. The glitz of Hollywood smashed up against the desperation of poverty‚ÄîAsk the Dust is a semi-autobiographical novel by Fante, covering his time struggling to be a writer in LA.
.
.
He influenced other writers, including Charles Bukowski‚Äîin the late 1970s, Bukowski stumbled upon Fante‚Äôs work at the Los Angeles Central Library and demand his publishers, Black Sparrow Press reprint his works. They did and created a resurgence of interest in all things John Fante. .
.
And I give you a quote from, Ask the Dust:
‚ÄúAh, Los Angeles! Dust and fog of your lonely streets, I am no longer lonely. Just you wait, all of you ghosts of this room, just you wait, because it will happen, as sure as there's a God in heaven.‚Äù

What if the universe is trying to get us to slow down? To stop producing. To stay home and let the earth breathe a little without all the extra pollution we cause daily. To take a step back and realize how we really impact earth and one another. That we aren't as significant or in control as we think we are. A virus can come through and wipe us all out but earth will still be here. We are all connected. Just like we can spread a disease, we can also spread üíõLOVEüíõ, kindness and positivity. Use this time for reflection of your contribution and the life you're living. Slow down and finally hear yourself again. The universe is always speaking to us if we are willing to listen.

insta_description:
Looking for problems?üîç You‚Äôre going to find them.
.
Waves in the ocean can represent obstacles. Especially when you‚Äôre swimming in it.
.
üåäüèä‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èüèä‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èYou always want to be on the lookout for waves. When the wave comes, time in right, and dive under so you can come out the other side practically unscathed.

Time it wrong or get blindsided (and both do happen despite your best efforts) and the wave can come crashing down on you and toss you around underwaterüåäü§∏‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èü§∏‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
If you have ever been mistreated by a wave, it‚Äôs easy to view them as problems. As obstacles‚ùå
.
And soon your relaxing swim in the ocean is replaced with panic from one wave to the next. You‚Äôre on the constant, anxious lookoutüîçüò≤
.
You can‚Äôt control the ocean. And if you‚Äôre focused on just the waves, you‚Äôre going to miss out on a lot of beauty that is all around you (and there is A LOT of beauty in the ocean)üíô
.
It‚Äôs like life.
.
If you‚Äôre looking for obstacles, you‚Äôre going to find them. If you‚Äôre living from obstacle to obstacle, you‚Äôre going to miss all the beauty that is around you.
.
üßò‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èHere‚Äôs a mental exercise you can do: replace the word obstacle with the word goodüßò‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
.
If you‚Äôre looking for the good, you‚Äôre going to find it. And you‚Äôre going to see the beauty that is around you.
.
Good = more time with your kids that you‚Äôve been desperate for. More time with your spouse because you have felt like you‚Äôre two ships passing in the night. More snuggle and kissy time with your fur babies. More tv watching. Getting chores done in and around the house with your extra time....
.
It‚Äôs all in what we choose to look at.

For full details of VERTIGO, see our main site: Movie-Locations.com (link on our profile page). üé¨

Overwhelmed by his own obsession, ex-cop Scottie (James Stewart) refashions lookalike actress Judy Barton (Kim Novak) into the perfect image of the dead Madeleine, in Alfred Hitchcock's 1950s masterpiece.

For the transformation of Judy into Madeleine, Hitchcock pulls off one of his dazzling visual coups, filling the seedy hotel room with an unearthly green neon glow. Although the film‚Äôs Hotel Empire has undergone a name change and a major facelift, you‚Äôll still recognise Judy‚Äôs lodging. It's now a Hitchcock-themed hotel, with Vertigo being screened continuously in the lobby.

It's a little surreal to walk into the hotel's entrance to be immediately faced with the scene of James Stewart walking through the same door in 1958 (that was a million to one chance of timing). For many years this was the York Hotel but ‚Äì three cheers! ‚Äì it‚Äôs since been relaunched with a long-overdue recognition of its heritage as Hotel Vertigo, in Lower Nob Hill just west of the downtown area. With a slick and stylish makeover, it‚Äôs a world away from its dowdy Fifties appearance ‚Äì but it‚Äôs still the setting of one of the cinema‚Äôs great scenes.

insta_description:
We met this couple by chance while on the road.
.

About to call it a night at a BLM site we noticed a couple in the distance with an RV what looked to be straight out of Breaking Bad. Once the sun set they kept flashing their headlights at us and start to make their way towards us. On the defensive we brace ourselves for what may happen. As they approach he then shouts from a safe distance "Our battery died! Would you mind helping us?". As I look them in the eyeballs she says "sorry! we kept flashing our lights weird so you wouldn't think we're murderers!". We laugh and proceeded to help this young couple who had just taken "antique" RV on the road for the first time. .
We ended up spending some time together that night and helped each other in different ways. .
There's so much more to this story but the moral of it all is to trust your gut. Through Matt and I's experiences (together and individually) we learned to just be open to others. There are more good people in this world than you may think. Thankfully this one wasn't Breaking Bad and instead told us where to find to find the best candy around cause you know candy and vans pair well together üòâüç≠üöê

Owner, Heather Jeffcoat, even wrote a book that emphasizes self care. While we are not minimizing what hands-on therapy can add for those with pelvic pain, incontinence, chronic pain and more - Much is still gained from observing one‚Äôs movement and using that information to lead us towards the rest of our clinical exam. When we see a patient move on that first visit and then put do a hands-on assessment, it is only to confirm what we have already observed. Every siiiingle thing that happens there‚Äôs a lesson to learn and grow into. It‚Äôs never comfortable. The more it hurts the more you can grow. Because it‚Äôs the moments when we‚Äôre faced with our biggest challenges that we are tested to see if we are ready to level up and I truly believe the universe works in favor of those who are willing to break societies mold and lead with a cosmically connected heart. What does a cosmic heart look like to me? One that remembers what it was to be connected. We are not separate. We were all created individually but composed of the same stardust. One that remembers taking from your neighbor or greedily choosing the betterment of self vs the betterment of the collective is separation. Being separate is one of the worst things you can be because once you separate you isolate more and more and more. You want for the self, you create for self, you buy for self and this me, me, me, culture divides. The uncomfortable thing about growing in a time like this is the only thing that will save us is remembering we‚Äôre better off together. Working together, getting creative on saving our planet together, helping lift each other up. Be it a FaceTime call, sending someone in need some groceries, being the person who remembers we all bleed the same blood and if our neighbor suffers because of lack of support we failed them.  Growing might feel like breaking at first but at least we‚Äôre all growing together.

I went to the mountains! I imagined mountains, spring air, nice time alone with no one around etc. well, it started snowing! It‚Äôs but off!! My nice little excursion with no WiFi turned into a freezing cold abyss! Not to mention my car doesn‚Äôt have 4 wheel drive üòÜ Well, someone helped me down the mountain. I was on an uphill and was trying to accelerate forward to turn around. He drove up and said just reverse! Back up that way and come down. I was so nervous! But I trusted because I had asked my dear lord for help. I backed up and got down safely only to park about a mile away refusing to go down any longer. As I was livin the life (not) bathrooming outside my car the man drove up and  said ‚Äúyeah I told you to back up because it never would have worked the other way. You were going against gravity.‚Äù And that part really got me. So today friends, let‚Äôs take the path of least resistance okay? Let‚Äôs not go against gravity. Let‚Äôs go with the flow of gravity. insta_description:
I just want to keep moving forward.

Forward to me, is learning to say no, learning to let people and things go.

It's not so much from a place of ego, but of self love and conserving my energy for the people and things that uplift me, bring me peace and support me.

Forward to me, is about leaving behind the drama, the bullshit, the stories, the attachments, energy vampires, the ones that are so stuck in their old patterns - they think they've evolved or are spiritual or whatever they imagine in their heads they are, when they really aren't - cuz the way they behave and treat others is exactly the same today as it was years ago. I don't have patience for those that choose to and want to stay trapped, asleep, fearful, sad, angry and not heal or genuinely try to, cuz I have way too much to work on myself.

Forward is being a better person for the planet as a whole. It's doing what I choose to with no gulit, shame or apologies. Without needing someone else's approval, "well meaning concern", worries, judgements, labels and opinions. Forward is believing in my true self implicitly, trusting life unconditionally no matter what.

Forward is breaking free. And all the glorious mistakes I make, will be mine to cherish.

Forward also, is the end of my existence on this beautiful planet. I do look forward to what happens when I drop this body', leaving it for donation or nature - whichever chooses it. (It's nature, the way of life, we ALL die, no one can fight or cheat death: you go when it's your time). I'm just going to keep on moving forward, learning lots of things, living my life to the fullest, being the best version of myself.

I'm moving forward to the real deal, breaking that ego down, be in a space of full honesty or silence. I'm moving forward to the world within. - Ramona Arena, 2020.

accessibility_caption: Image may contain: 1 person, food
insta_description:
The past few weeks Forever With Us has helped the families of Hazel, Matthew, and Sebastian from CHOC Children‚Äôs Hospital. Honoring our precious angels below and please keep their families in your prayersü§ç:
‚Äî
Sweet and thoughtful Hazel was diagnosed with medulloblastoma and fought this disease that she was so undeserving of. Hazel loved unicorns, rainbows and all things shiny. She stayed in the hospital since May 2019 and was so loved by all that had the privilege of caring for her. She passed away peacefully at six years old, with those who loved her at her side. 
From our board member Eric who knew Hazel: ‚ÄúShe was everyone's best friend on the 5th floor. The nurses and volunteers all have a Hazel story. She was full of joy and it was contagious. We miss Hazel!‚Äù
‚Äî
Matthew was a 23 month old boy who was diagnosed with neuroblastoma in March of 2018 and underwent treatment for two months until May 2018. He sadly relapsed in March of 2019 and fought this cancer for almost a year before passing away in February of 2020. Matthew was the youngest of his siblings and was always known for lighting up the room with his smile. Despite his progressive disease, Matthew was known to run and play with his brothers. He was truly a little angel and will greatly be missed by his CHOC family. Matthew is forever with us.
‚Äî
Sebastian was a strong and beautiful baby boy¬†who first came to CHOC at 5 months old and gained his angel wings at 17 months after a year long battle with childhood cancer. He was diagnosed with a malignant brain tumor and underwent extensive treatment. Sebastian was a delight to care for by CHOC staff and was so loved by his family. He will be greatly missed by all those whose lives he touched. Sebastian is forever with us.

So I started to count: One, two, three, four, five...Then it was gone.‚Äù - LOST (Pilot episode)
Socially isolating never felt so good in my lungs. 
Work is taking its toll, for sure. But we‚Äôre getting through this. One day at a time. I let the fear take over for a little bit each day. And then I get back to work. Just like all of us have to do. We have to keep moving. Just like running or hiking a trail. You can stop at any point. But you‚Äôll still have to make a decision to keep going, whether it be forward, or back the way you came. That‚Äôs why I love trail running, because it teaches me perseverance. And we could all use a little perseverance right now.

insta_description:
Social isolation at its finest! In all seriousness, this has been an indescribable week here not just in LA, but globally. What sticks out the most to me, and it absolutely breaks my heart, is how cruel humanity can be in times of crisis. The reports say it all - people stealing hand sanitizer and masks from hospitals and clinics, people ripping toilet paper rolls from the hands of the elderly, and people fighting over commodities that hold no real value.

In times like this, you would hope humanity would manifest compassion. Instead, we envelop ourselves in greed and selfishness. 
The beauty of this is - it doesn‚Äôt have to be that way. We can all change it one person at a time. I challenge everyone to go out of their way to do something nice for a stranger. In times of fear, even a simple smile goes a long way. Let‚Äôs be human again. 
I read this quote the other day, and it really resonated with me so I wanted to share it with you all ‚ÄúKindness makes you the most beautiful person in the world, regardless of what you look like.‚Äù

insta_description:
Yesterday, between the California rain showers, the sun came out and I took my dog on a walk.  My mind was filled with worries of what we are experiencing with covid-19 and the impact it‚Äôs having across the globe.  As I walked around my neighborhood I saw people out happily walking their dogs.  I saw neighbors on bikes and children laughing as they rode alongside their siblings and parents.  My mind started to settle as I witnessed the community coming outside and while keeping their distance showing their solidarity.  Then I walked by a house with this sign in their yard. ‚ÄúYou are not alone.‚Äù We are not alone!  Even though we may be distancing socially we do not need to isolate and disappear from our communities, families and friends.  We can still connect thanks to the amazing technologies of our current age.  As a clinical psychologist, I am seeing an increase in anxiety, stress and depression with many of the people that I work with.  And while there seems to be a collective anxiety occurring, there is also a collective solidarity.  From the neighbors communing from a distance, to the families gaining reunited togetherness as they‚Äôre confined home, to the positive social media posts of unity around the world...we are not alone and we will endure. üåé Know that ‚ÄúThis too shall pass.‚Äù YOU are not alone.

California schools are closed. Stores are empty. People are taking distance precautions and scared to visit their loved ones.
